# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-b-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The **automotive industry** comprises a wide range of companies and organisations involved in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing, selling, repairing, and modification of motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] It is one of the world's largest industries by revenue with global automotive market at ~$2.75 trillion in 2025.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The word *automotive* comes from the Greek *autos* (self), and Latin *motivus* (of motion), referring to any form of self-powered vehicle.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] This term, as proposed by Elmer Sperry (1860–1930), first came into use to describe automobiles in 1898.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The automotive industry began in the 1860s with hundreds of manufacturers pioneering the horseless carriage.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Early car manufacturing involved manual assembly by a human worker.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The process evolved from engineers working on a stationary car to a conveyor belt system where the car passed through multiple stations of more specialised engineers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In the 1960s, robotic equipment was introduced, and most cars are now mainly assembled by automated machinery.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] For many decades, the United States led the world in total automobile production, with the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Big Three General Motors, Ford Motor Company, and Chrysler being the world's three largest auto manufacturers for a time, and G.M. and Ford remaining the two largest until the mid-2000s.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In 1929, before the Great Depression, the world had 32,028,500 automobiles in use, of which the U.S. automobile enterprises produced more than 90%.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] At that time, the U.S. had one car per 4.87 persons.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] After 1945, the U.S. produced around three-quarters of the world's auto production.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In 1980, the U.S. was overtaken by Japan and then became a world leader again in 1994.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Japan narrowly passed the U.S. in production during 2006 and 2007, and in 2008 also China, which in 2009 took the top spot (from Japan) with 13.8 million units, although the U.S. surpassed Japan in 2011, to become the second-largest automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced more than 31 million vehicles in a year, after breaking 30 million in 2023, reaching 29 million for the first time in 2017 and 28 million the year before.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced the most passenger cars in the world, with Japan, India, Germany, and South Korea trailing.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] This was achieved by Chinese car companies signing joint ventures with foreign manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] From 1970 (140 models) to 1998 (260 models) to 2012 (684 models), the number of automobile models in the U.S. has grown nearly twofold.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Safety is a state that implies being protected from any risk, danger, damage, or cause of injury.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In the automotive industry, safety means that users, operators, or manufacturers do not face any risk or danger coming from the motor vehicle or its spare parts.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Safety for the automobiles themselves implies that there is no risk of damage.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Safety in the automotive industry is particularly important and therefore highly regulated.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Automobiles and other motor vehicles have to comply with a certain number of regulations, whether local or international, in order to be accepted on the market.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The standard ISO 26262, is considered one of the best practice frameworks for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In case of safety issues, danger, product defect, or faulty procedure during the manufacturing of the motor vehicle, the maker can request to return either a batch or the entire production run.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] This procedure is called product recall.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Product recalls happen in every industry and can be production-related or stem from raw materials.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Product and operation tests and inspections at different stages of the value chain are made to avoid these product recalls by ensuring end-user security and safety and compliance with the automotive industry requirements.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] However, the automotive industry is still particularly concerned about product recalls, which cause considerable financial consequences.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In 2007, there were about 806 million cars and light trucks on the road, consuming over 980 billion litres (980,000,000 m3) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The automobile is a primary mode of transportation for many developed economies.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The Detroit branch of Boston Consulting Group predicted that, by 2014, one-third of world demand would be in the four BRIC markets (Brazil, Russia, India, and China).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Meanwhile, in developed countries, the automotive industry has slowed.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] It is also expected that this trend will continue, especially as the younger generations of people (in highly urbanised countries) no longer want to own a car, and prefer other modes of transport.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Other potentially powerful automotive markets are Iran and Indonesia.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Emerging automobile markets already buy more cars than established markets.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Power study, emerging markets accounted for 51 percent of the global light-vehicle sales in 2010.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The study, performed in 2010 expected this trend to accelerate.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] However, more recent reports (2012) confirmed the opposite; namely that the automotive industry was slowing down even in BRIC countries.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In the United States, vehicle sales peaked in 2000, at 17.8 million units.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In July 2021, the European Commission released its "Fit for 55" legislation package, which contains important guidelines for the future of the automotive industry; all new cars on the European market must be zero-emission vehicles from 2035.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car manufacturers including GM, Ford, Volvo, BYD Auto, Jaguar Land Rover and Mercedes-Benz committed to "work towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Major car manufacturing nations like the United States, Germany, China, Japan and South Korea, as well as Volkswagen, Toyota, Peugeot, Honda, Nissan and Hyundai, did not pledge.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The global automotive industry is a major consumer of water.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Some estimates surpass 180,000 L (39,000 imp gal) of water per car manufactured, depending on whether tyre production is included.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Production processes that use a significant volume of water include surface treatment, painting, coating, washing, cooling, air-conditioning, and boilers, not counting component manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Paintshop operations consume especially large amounts of water because equipment running on water-based products must also be cleaned with water.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] In 2022, Tesla's Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg ran into legal challenges due to droughts and falling groundwater levels in the region.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Brandenburg's Economy Minister Joerg Steinbach said that while water supply was sufficient during the first stage, more would be needed once Tesla expands the site.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The factory would nearly double the water consumption in the Gruenheide area, with 1.4 million cubic meters being contracted from local authorities per year — enough for a city of around 40,000 people.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Steinbach said that the authorities would like to drill for more water there and outsource any additional supply if necessary.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] : US had produced more than 80% of motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] : India overtakes Germany to become 4th largest automobile producer.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The OICA counts over 50 countries that assemble, manufacture, or disseminate automobiles.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Of those, only 15 countries (**boldfaced** in the list below) currently possess the capability to design original production automobiles from the ground up, and 17 countries (listed below) have at least one million produced vehicles a year (as of 2023).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] All ten remained as the ten largest car makers by sales until the merger between Fiat-Chrysler and the PSA Group in early 2021; only Renault was degraded to 11th place, in 2022, when being surpassed by both BMW (which became the 10th largest in 2021) and Chang'an.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The eighteen largest as of 2013 have remained in the top 20 as of 2017, except Mitsubishi which fell out of top 20 in 2016, while Geely fell out of the top 20 in 2014 and 2015 but re-entered it in 2016.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Mercedes-Benz Group held a combined 6.2% stake in the Renault–Nissan–Mitsubishi Alliance, and the Renault-Nissan-Mitsubishi Alliance also held a combined 6.2% stake in Mercedes-Benz Group until 2021.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] Until 2022, China required foreign automotive firms to form joint ventures in order to access their market.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/automotive-industry] The policy led to quality improvement across the industry.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] In a piston engine, the **bore** (or **cylinder bore**) is the diameter of each cylinder.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] The stroke ratio, determined by dividing the bore by the stroke, traditionally indicated whether an engine was designed for power at high engine speeds (rpm) or torque at lower engine speeds.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] The term "bore" can also be applied to the bore of a locomotive cylinder or steam engine pistons.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] The term **bore** also applies to the cylinder of a steam locomotive or steam engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] The bore pitch is always larger than the inside diameter of the cylinder (the bore and piston diameter) since it includes the thickness of both cylinder walls and any water passage separating them.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] This is one of the first dimensions required when developing a new engine, since it limits maximum cylinder size (and therefore, indirectly, maximum displacement), and determines the length of the engine (L4, 6, 8) or of that bank of cylinders (V6, V8 etc.).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] In some older engines (such as the Chevrolet Gen-2 "Stovebolt" inline-six, the GMC straight-6 engine, the Buick Straight-eight, and the Chrysler "Slant 6") the bore pitch is additionally extended to allow more material between the main bearing webs in the block.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] For example, in an L6 the first pair (#1 & 2), center pair (#3 & 4), and rear pair (#5 & 6) of cylinders that share a pair of main bearings have a smaller pitch than between #2 & 3 and #4 & 5 that "bridge" a main bearing.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] Since the start-up expense of casting an engine block is very high, this is a strong incentive to retain this dimension for as long as possible to amortize the tooling cost over a large number of engines.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] If and when the engine is further refined, modified or enlarged, the bore pitch may be the only dimension retained from its predecessor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] The bore diameter is frequently increased to the limit of minimal wall thickness, the water passage is eliminated between each pair of adjacent cylinders, the deck height is increased to accommodate a longer stroke, etc. but in general if the bore pitch is the same, the engines are related.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] All of these engines retain the original 4.460" bore pitch distance set down in 1956.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] "Hybrid" is the term commonly used to identify an engine modified for high performance by adapting a cylinder head from another (sometimes completely different) brand, size, model or type engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] Note: using a later head of the same engine "family" isn't a true hybrid, but mere modernization.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] In some cases, two heads from the donor (source) engine are joined end-to-end to match the number of cylinders on the subject engine (such as using three cylinders each of two V8 heads on a Chevrolet inline-six).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bore-engine] Identical or extremely similar bore pitch is what makes this possible, or (almost) impossible.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The **Bristol 411** is an automobile which was built by the British manufacturer Bristol Cars from 1969 to 1976.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] It was the fifth series of Chrysler-V8 engined Bristol models.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The car was rated highly for its comfort, performance and handling by contemporary reviewers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] With the 411, Bristol, for the first time since the 407 was introduced, made a change of engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] Although they were still using a Chrysler V8 engine, the old A type engine was gone.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] Replacing it was the much larger big-block B series engine of 6,277 cc (383.0 cu in) - compared to the 5,211 cc of the 410.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] This much larger engine gave the 411 an estimated 30 percent more power and torque than had been found in the 410.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] To cope with this extra power, a limited slip differential was fitted.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The interior showed a number of important changes from the Bristol 410.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The traditional Blümel twin-spoke steering wheel was replaced by a more practical three-spoked leather-wrapped wheel, which, as a result of the traditional Bristol badge being removed from the front of the car, was the *only* place where this badge was retained.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] Over its seven years in production, the 411 showed a number of changes.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The 1971 **Series 2** added self-levelling suspension and a metric odometer, while the **Series 3** from a year later had a lower compression ratio and completely revised styling.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] This edition was the first Bristol to possess the four-headlamp layout that was oddly anticipated by some of the company's earliest models, and to power this a bigger alternator was used.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] For the **Series 4** of 1974, the compression ratio was reduced dramatically (from 9.5:1 to 8.2:1) but this was compensated for by using a larger version of the B series engine with a capacity of 6,556 cc (400.1 cubic inches).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] Previously, engine power outputs in the United States were quoted as gross power.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] By the time the larger engine was supplied to Bristol, the figures were quoted as net power outputs.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The Series 4 & 5 cars engines produced 265 bhp (198 kW) and 335 lb⋅ft (454 N⋅m) torque.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The rear lights were also changed using vertically mounted rectangular Lucas clusters, that carried over to the early 603 models.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The **Series 5** made from 1975 to 1976 had the original Bristol badge restored and was the first Bristol to feature inertia reel seat belts.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] In the 2010s Bristol Cars offered a modernised version of the Bristol 411, the Series 6.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] This was a refurbished version based on existing 411s.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/bristol-411] The only engine is the fuel injected 5.9 litre Chrysler Magnum V8 as used in the later Bristol Blenheim, allowing for up to 400 hp (298 kW) depending on the customer's desires.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The **Cadillac Gage Commando**, frequently denoted as the **M706** in U.S. military service, is an American armored car designed to be amphibious.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] It was engineered by Cadillac Gage specifically for the United States Military Police Corps during the Vietnam War as an armed convoy escort vehicle.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The Commando was one of the first vehicles to combine the traditionally separate roles of an armored personnel carrier and a conventional armored car, much like the Soviet BTR-40.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Its notable height, amphibious capability, and waterproofed engine allowed American crews to fight effectively in the jungles of Vietnam by observing their opponents over thick vegetation and fording the country's deep rivers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The Commando was eventually produced in three distinct marks: the V-100, V-150, and V-200, all of which were modified for a number of diverse battlefield roles.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] An unlicensed copy of the Commando series, the Bravia Chaimite, was also manufactured in Portugal.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] After the U.S. military's disengagement from South Vietnam, the Commando series was gradually retired from active U.S. service.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] It was superseded in the Military Police Corps by the derivative M1117 armored security vehicle during the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-100 series of vehicles was developed in the early 1960s by the Terra-Space division of the Cadillac Gage company of Warren, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] By 1962 a patent was filed and received by Terra-Space for a vehicle then only known as the **Commando**.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The first prototype emerged in 1963, and the production variants entered service in 1964.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The vehicle is equipped with four-wheel drive and uses axles similar to the ones used in the M35 series of trucks.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The engine is a gasoline-powered 360-cubic-inch Chrysler V8, same as in the early gas models of the M113 armored personnel carriers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Its 5-speed manual transmission allows it to traverse relatively rough terrain.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The M706 has a road speed of 62 mph (100 km/h), and can travel across water at 3 mph (4.8 km/h).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] A Commando's armor consists of high hardness alloy steel called Cadaloy, which protects against projectiles up to 7.62×51mm.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Partly because of its armor, the M706 has an unloaded mass of over 7 tons.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] As a result, a common problem with the vehicle is rear axle failure caused by the extreme weight.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] However, because the armor also provides the monocoque structural framework, it can be lighter than a soft vehicle to which armor has been added, and the angle of the armor also helps protect against hits and mine blasts.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-100 was available in turret and open-top models.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Factory prototype turret options included the T-60, T-70, and T-90.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The T-60 featured a combination of either two .50 caliber machine guns, two .30 caliber machine guns, or one of each, and had manual traverse.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The specific .30 caliber machine gun options were extremely varied, with from factory configurations including the M1919A4E1, M37, M73, M219, and MG42.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Later the M60 and FN MAG were also added to the list of options.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The Cadillac Gage company also intended to use the solenoid trigger equipped fixed machine gun version of the Stoner 63 weapon system, but this was dropped after tests showed the smaller caliber cartridge to be unsuited to this role.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The T-90 featured a single 20 mm cannon with power traverse.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The T-70, developed for police use, featured 4 tear gas launchers, vision blocks all around the turret for 360-degree vision, and no other weapons.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The T-70 and T-90 were not put into mass production; instead, a modified T-60—with the guns centrally mounted, rather than along the outer edges—became the standard.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] A variant of this turret featuring the 7.62 mm General Electric Minigun was also developed.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] In addition an open-topped variant with a central parapet was developed.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The intended usage of this variant was to be a mortar portee, but a total of five machine gun mounts could also be fitted.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] There were 2 in front, one in the rear all three M2 Browning or Mk 19 capable and one folding pintle point on each side capable of mounting any .30 caliber machine gun such as the M1919 Browning machine gun, M60 or any other machine gun of that class.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] An enclosed raised superstructure "pod" was also developed for converting the V-100 into either a command vehicle or for police use.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The variants for police work featured special elongated firing ports for better angles of fire for tear gas grenade launchers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Relatively large-gunned variants of the V-100 began appearing in 1964, when Cadillac Gage marketed the Commando against the Alvis Saladin and Panhard AML-90 for a Royal Saudi Army requirement specifying a wheeled armoured vehicle equipped with a large semi-automatic cannon.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] A number of V-150s were later successfully tested and offered with a Mecar low-pressure 90 mm smoothbore gun.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] With the new turret and gun, the V-150 was manned by a crew of three, although it retained enough space for eight additional passengers if no additional shell racks were added.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] At maximum capacity its hull could store up to thirty-nine rounds of 90 mm ammunition and still seat four additional passengers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Subsequent V-150 models incorporated a slightly larger turret armed with a much more powerful Cockerill Mk.III 90 mm gun, the same as that carried by the EE-9 Cascavel.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] A third fire support option involved the retrofitting of the Commando chassis with the complete turret and 76 mm L23A1 gun of the British FV101 Scorpion tracked reconnaissance vehicle.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Marketing for the V-150 family was halted in 2000.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] In 2010, Federal Defense Industries announced that they entered into an agreement with Textron Marine & Land Systems in order to provide authorized aftermarket parts, support and other types of assistance for the V-100/150/200 since FDI maintains a technical library for spare parts.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] In 2011, Napco entered into an agreement with Textron to provide authorized aftermarket parts, support and other types of assistance for the V-100/150.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The Commando was originally deployed to South Vietnam in September 1963 for use by the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Army Military Police, United States Air Force, United States Marine Corps and allied forces including the Army of the Republic of Vietnam (ARVN).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] It was introduced in Vietnam as the XM706 Commando first to the ARVN who loaned the first examples to the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Army had purchased its own version of the armored car, the XM706E1, later standardized as the M706.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Army it was affectionately known as *the Duck*, or *the V*.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The main differences between the XM706 and XM706E1/M706 were in the design of the gas tank fill port covers, side windows, front vision blocks, and most importantly in the weaponry.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The XM706 featured two .30-06 caliber M37 machine guns, while the XM706E1/M706 for the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Army featured two 7.62mm NATO M73 machine guns for better ammunition commonality with existing weapons.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The ARVN, on the other hand, were still using a variety of weapons in the .30-06 caliber and had relevant ammunition in their supply train.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] In practice, the ARVN found the standard two-gun armament to be lacking and often mounted an additional M1919A4 machine gun on a standard tripod mount at the rear radio operator's hatch.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] A number of their V-100s were also refitted with the combination turret armament of one M37 and one .50 BMG-caliber M2HB machine gun.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-100 in with the ARVN mainly saw service in armored car elements of armored cavalry units, but also as part of the mechanized platoons of the South Vietnamese Regional Forces.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Compared to the American counterparts ARVN V-100 units had larger crews, including a commander riding shotgun, and a radio operator outside the rear hatch.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Another model, the XM706E2, was supplied to the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Air Force for base protection purposes, post-attack reconnaissance against munitions and EOD use.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The XM706E2 featured no turret and an open-topped center parapet.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] In practice a variety of weapons were mounted on USAF XM706E2s, but the most common configuration was one M2HB machine gun and one M60 machine gun.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Other equipment included the XM174 40 mm grenade launcher and searchlights.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The 3rd Security Police Group of the United States Air Force at Clark Air Base Republic of the Philippines was still operating the "Duck" as a Fire-Team vehicle until it received M1026 HMMWVs in the fall of 1988.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The vehicles were then semi-retired, and occasionally used as "steel bunkers” at the gates, because of the difficulty in keeping the 20-year-old vehicles running.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-100 carries a maximum crew of two with up to 10 passengers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] In road patrol, convoy duty and base defense use by the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Army's Military Police, it usually had a crew of two: driver and gunner.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Additional armament often included two or three top-mounted M2 or M60 machine guns.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Other weapons such as M134 Miniguns were also sometimes used.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Passengers could also use their personal weapons to fire through the vehicle's various gun ports.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] In spite of its effectiveness during the Vietnam War, the U.S. military made limited use of the V-100s after the war, deploying only small units of the armored cars with U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Army Military Police platoons at the Herlong Army Depot in California during the 1970s, or other related sites across the country.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The remaining V-100s were expended as "hard targets" for tank and machinegun ranges throughout various military installations.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] It was used by the Malaysian Army in Second Malayan Emergency and Royal Malaysia Police (GOF- Pasukan Gerakan Am) until now.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] They are used by the Royal Thai Army, and were deployed in the Burmese border as part of the Battle of Border Post 9631 in 2001.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The vehicle is also used by many SWAT units in the U.S. and gendarmerie forces overseas.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-100 is the predecessor of the M1117 armored security vehicle which was used by the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Army for convoy protection and other duties in Iraq and Afghanistan.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] For many years the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) operated 2 V-100s for use by the LAPD Metropolitan Division D Platoon.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The LAPD obtained the V-100s from the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Department of Energy in the early 1980s for Los Angeles' hosting of the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The vehicles were disarmed, and upgraded with a 10-foot (3.0 m) battering ram used to breach buildings in a raid.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The battering ram's flat end was decorated with a smiley face and captioned "Have a nice day." The LAPD has retired the V-100 vehicles, with their last major deployment being the 1997 North Hollywood shootout.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Cadillac Gage's basic V-100 vehicle spawned an entire series of vehicles.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] This development was continued even after the production and further development of the system was passed to Marine and Land Division of the Textron company.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] These included updated 4×4 vehicles, but also expanded 6×6 vehicles utilizing a similar design and some basic components.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-150 was a hybrid variant which was based on the V-200 but had some V-100 features.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] It could be equipped with diesel or gasoline engines and most were produced for the Saudi Arabian National Guard as the *V-150S*.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-150 was initially fitted with the same Chrysler V8 gasoline engine and three-speed transmission as the V-100, but these were later superseded by a Cummins six-cylinder engine and a four-speed automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Unlike the V-200, all V-150s retained the same size and dimensions of the earlier V-100s; however, they were manufactured with heavier axles and modified suspension units.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-150's hull was also designed specifically to carry heavier weapons systems, such as large smoothbore guns for fire support and anti-tank purposes.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] In the 1980s Portugal updated its Chaimites (originally built between 1967 and 1974) with a 90 mm turret (V-400), but the Portuguese Army also bought 15 examples of the U.S.-made V-150 Commando.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The Philippine Army continue to use their V-150s in 2017, when several photos appeared on social media of a vehicle with heavy wooden planks and flattened ammunition crates were applied as improvised armor against ISIL insurgents in the southern islands.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The effectiveness of the improvised vehicle armor against proper rocket-propelled grenades is doubtful, but it has been judged to reduce some of the RPG's damage.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] On June 7, 2023, LAV-150s upgraded by Larsen & Toubro were tested in Bulacan.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The HMV-150 is a modernized and upgraded variant of the V-150 created by Thailand in 2017, designed by Panus Assembly.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The HMV-150 has a new design to respond to new threats and especially to offer more protection against mines and IEDs.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The internal layout of the vehicle is also modified to offer more internal space, giving a capacity to carry up to ten military personnel.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The original V-150 only had the capacity to transport five people.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The vehicle is fitted with a new 8.9 liter Cummins ISL engine Euro 3 developing 350 hp. coupled to a new Allison 4500 automatic transmission with six gears.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The HMV-150 can achieve a maximum road speed of 110 km/h (68 mph).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] An unknown amount of HMV-150s have been delivered.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Currently they are being operated by the Royal Thai Armed Forces, most especially the Royal Thai Navy and the Royal Thai Marine Corps through donations.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The HMV-150 has been further developed from 2018 as the HMV-420.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-200 was essentially an enlarged version of the V-100 and utilized many components of the U.S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] This version was designed to the specifications of the Singapore Armed Forces (SAF) and entered service in 1968.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] It was fitted with a custom diesel engine and was notably heavier than the V-100.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] ST Kinetics upgraded the Singaporean fleet of V-200 vehicles in 2002 with electric turret drives and made some detail improvements to both the engine and transmission.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The Singapore Army continued to hold two hundred V-200s in reserve until 2015, when they were formally retired and replaced by the Peacekeeper Protected Response Vehicle (PRV).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Fifty V-200s were operated by the Republic of Singapore Air Force for on-base security and equipped with Swedish-manufactured RBS 70 surface to air missiles in a turret mount.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] It is unclear whether these were retired in 2015 as well.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] Originally named as the V-300, the LAV-300 is a 6×6 variant originally designed for a heavy weapons support role.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The V-600 is a much heavier version of the V-300 and was intended to fulfill heavier weapons support.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/cadillac-gage-commando] The primary version is equipped with a 105 mm turret.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A **carburetor** (also spelled **carburettor** or **carburetter**) is a device used by a gasoline internal combustion engine to control and mix air and fuel entering the engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The primary method of adding fuel to the intake air is through the Venturi effect or Bernoulli's principle or with a pitot tube in the main metering circuit, though various other components are also used to provide extra fuel or air in specific circumstances.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Since the 1990s, carburetors have been largely replaced by fuel injection for cars and trucks, but carburetors are still used by some small engines (e.g. lawnmowers, generators, and concrete mixers) and motorcycles.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In addition, they are still widely used on piston-engine–driven aircraft.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Diesel engines have always used fuel injection instead of carburetors, as they do not compress an air-fuel mix and instead require fuel injection much later in the compression stroke.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The term "carburetor" is derived from the English verb *carburet*, meaning "to charge with hydrocarbons"; in early motoring books the product of the carburetor is *carburetted air*, i.e. air charged with hydrocarbon vapour.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This meaning superseded that from the late eighteenth century in which *carburet* was a noun for which we now use the word *carbide*.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A carburetor charges the intake air with vapour from a hydrocarbon-based fuel, such as petrol or autogas.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The name is spelled "carburetor" in American English and "carburettor" in British English.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Colloquial abbreviations include "carb" in the UK and North America or "carby" in Australia.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Air from the atmosphere enters the carburetor (usually via an air cleaner), has fuel added within the carburetor, then the air fuel mixture leaves the carburetor and enters the inlet manifold, then through the inlet valve(s), and finally into the combustion chamber.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Most engines use a single carburetor shared among all of the cylinders, though some high-performance engines historically had multiple carburetors and/or throats.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] If the tube is a constant diameter the configuration is slightly simpler than in the cross-section diagram shown above right.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In most cases (except for the *accelerator pump*), the driver pressing the throttle pedal does not directly increase the fuel entering the engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Instead, the airflow through the carburetor increases, which in turn increases the amount of fuel drawn into the intake mixture.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a reduction of area along the air flow rather than from ambient pressure to the fuel entry point the effect can be described as the Venturi effect, but that is still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a dynamic pressure (facing the incoming air) within the air entry point rather than from ambient pressure instead the carbureter can be described as the Pitot tube type, but that is also still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The actual fuel and air flows are more complicated and need correction.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This might be done variously at lower speeds or higher speeds, or over the whole range by a variable emulsion device to add air to the fuel after the main jets/s.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Zenith-Stromberg) variable jet carburetors, it was mainly controlled by varying the jet size.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The orientation of the carburetor is a key design consideration.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Older engines used **updraft** carburetors, where the air enters from below the carburetor and exits through the top.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] From the late 1930s, **downdraft** carburetors become more commonly used (especially in the United States), along with **side draft** carburetors (especially in Europe).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The main metering circuit usually consists of barrel/s which reduces to a narrow part where the air is at its highest speed, forming a choke or venturi.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Fuel is usually introduced into the air stream at that narrow part through small tubes leading from the main jet.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The change in area is only necessary for a Venturi carburetor but in other configurations the barrel/s can be of constant area with the fuel entry anywhere along it.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Downstream of a choke or venturi is a throttle (usually in the form of a butterfly valve) which is used to control the amount of air entering the carburetor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In a car, this throttle is usually mechanically connected to the vehicle's throttle pedal, which varies engine speed.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] At lesser throttle openings, the air speed may be insufficient to maintain the main fuel flow, so then the fuel may be supplied by the carburetor's idle and off-idle circuits usually near the narrow gap between the edge of the butterfly plate and the body to give sufficient local air speed.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] At greater throttle openings, the speed of air increases, which lowers the pressure of the air and draws more fuel into the airstream.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] At the same time, the reduced manifold vacuum results in less fuel flow through the idle and off-idle circuits.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] During cold weather fuel vaporizes less readily and tends to condense on the walls of the intake manifold, starving the cylinders of fuel and making cold starts difficult.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Additional fuel is required (for a given amount of air) to start and run the engine until it warms up, provided by a *choke valve*.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] While the engine is warming up the choke valve is partially closed, restricting the flow of air at the entrance to the carburetor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This increases the vacuum in the main metering circuit, causing more fuel to be supplied to the engine via the main jets.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Prior to the late 1950s the choke was manually operated by the driver, often using a lever or knob on the dashboard.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Since then, automatic chokes became more commonplace.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] These either use a bimetallic thermostat to automatically regulate the choke based on the temperature of the engine's coolant liquid, an electrical resistance heater to do so, or air drawn through a tube connected to an engine exhaust source.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A choke left closed after the engine has warmed up increases the engine's fuel consumption and exhaust gas emissions, and causes the engine to run rough and lack power due to an over-rich fuel mixture.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] However, excessive fuel can flood an engine and prevent it from starting.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] To remove the excess fuel, many carburetors with automatic chokes allow it to be held open (by manually, depressing the accelerator pedal to the floor and briefly holding it there while cranking the starter) to allow extra air into the engine until the excess fuel is cleared out.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Another method used by carburetors to improve the operation of a cold engine is a *fast idle cam*, which is connected to the choke and prevents the throttle from closing fully while the choke is in operation.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The resulting increase in idle speed provides a more stable idle for a cold engine (by better atomizing the cold fuel) and helps the engine warm up quicker.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The system within a carburetor that meters fuel when the engine is running at low RPM.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The idle circuit is generally activated by vacuum near the (near closed) throttle plate, where the air speed increases to cause a low-pressure area in the idle passage/port, thus causing fuel to flow through the idle jet.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The idle jet is set at some constant value by the carburetor manufacturer, thus flowing a specified amount of fuel.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Many carburetors use an off-idle circuit, which includes an additional fuel jet which is briefly used as the throttle starts to open.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This jet is located in a low-pressure area caused by the high air speed near the (partly closed) throttle.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The additional fuel it provides is used to compensate for the reduced vacuum that occurs when the throttle is opened, thus smoothing the transition from the idle circuit to the main metering circuit.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In a four-stroke engine it is often desirable to provide extra fuel to the engine at high loads (to increase the power output and reduce engine knocking).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A 'power valve', which is a spring-loaded valve in the carburetor that is held shut by engine vacuum, is often used to do so.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] As the airflow through the carburetor increases, the reduced manifold vacuum pulls the power valve open, allowing more fuel into the main metering circuit.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In a two-stroke engine, the carburetor power valve operates in the opposite manner: in most circumstances the valve allows extra fuel into the engine, then at a certain engine RPM it closes to reduce the fuel entering the engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This is done in order to extend the engine's maximum RPM, since many two-stroke engines can temporarily achieve higher RPM with a leaner air-fuel ratio.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This is not to be confused with the unrelated exhaust power valve arrangements used on two-stroke engines.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A metering rod or step-up rod system is sometimes used as an alternative to a power valve in a four-stroke engine in order to supply extra fuel at high loads.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] One end of the rods is tapered, which sits in the main metering jets and acts as a valve for fuel flow in the jets.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] At high engine loads, the rods are lifted away from the jets (either mechanically or using manifold vacuum), increasing the volume of fuel flow through the jet.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] These systems have been used by the Rochester Quadrajet and in the 1950s Carter carburetors.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] While the main metering circuit can adequately supply fuel to the engine in steady-state conditions, the inertia of fuel (being higher than that of air) causes a temporary shortfall as the throttle is opened.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Therefore, an accelerator pump is often used to briefly provide extra fuel as the throttle is opened.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] When the driver presses the throttle pedal, a small piston or diaphragm pump injects extra fuel directly into the carburetor throat.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The accelerator pump can also be used to "prime" an engine with extra fuel prior to attempting a cold start.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In order to ensure an adequate supply at all times, carburetors include a reservoir of fuel, called a "float chamber" or "float bowl".
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Fuel is delivered to the float chamber by a fuel pump or by gravity with the fuel tank located higher than the carburetor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A floating inlet valve regulates the fuel entering the float chamber, assuring a constant level.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In some small engines that may instead of a float chamber just use a fuel tank close below the carburetor and use the fuel suction to supply the fuel.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Unlike in a fuel injected engine, the fuel system in a carbureted engine is not pressurized.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] For engines where the intake air travelling through the carburetor is pressurized (such as where the carburetor is downstream of a supercharger) the entire carburetor must be contained in an airtight pressurized box to operate.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] However, this is not necessary where the carburetor is upstream of the supercharger.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Problems of fuel boiling and vapor lock can occur in carbureted engines, especially in hotter climates.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Since the float chamber is located close to the engine, heat from the engine (including for several hours after the engine is shut off) can cause the fuel to heat up to the point of vaporization.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This causes air bubbles in the fuel (similar to the air bubbles that necessitate brake bleeding), which prevents the flow of fuel and is known as 'vapor lock'.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] If an engine must be operated when the carburetor is not in an upright orientation (for example in a chainsaw or airplane), a float chamber and gravity activated float valve would not be suitable.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Instead, a diaphragm chamber is typically used.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This consists of a flexible diaphragm on one side of the fuel chamber, connected to a needle valve which regulates the fuel entering the chamber.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber (controlled by the throttling valve/butterfly valve) decreases, the diaphragm moves inward (downward), which closes the needle valve to admit less fuel.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber increases, the diaphragm moves outward (upward) which opens the needle valve to admit more fuel, allowing the engine to generate more power.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A balanced state is reached which creates a steady fuel reservoir level, that remains constant in any orientation.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The basic design for a carburetor consists of a single venturi (main metering circuit), though designs with two or four venturi (two-barrel and four-barrel carburetors respectively) are also quite commonplace.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Typically the barrels consist of "primary" barrel(s) used for lower load situations and secondary barrel(s) activating when required to provide additional air/fuel at higher loads.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The primary and secondary venturi are often sized differently and incorporate different features to suit the situations in which they are used.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Many four-barrel carburetors use two primary and two secondary barrels.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A four-barrel design of two primary and two secondary barrels was commonly used in V8 engines to conserve fuel at low engine speeds while still affording an adequate supply at high.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The use of multiple carburetors (e.g., a carburetor for each cylinder or pair of cylinders) also results in the intake air being drawn through multiple venturi.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Some high-performance engines have used multiple two-barrel or four-barrel carburetors, for example six two-barrel carburetors on Ferrari V12s.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In 1826, American engineer Samuel Morey received a patent for a "gas or vapor engine", which had a carburetor that mixed turpentine and air.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In 1888/1889 German engineer Siegfried Marcus produced a car powered by a petrol engine (which also debuted the first magneto ignition system).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Karl Benz introduced his single-cylinder four-stroke powered Benz Patent-Motorwagen in 1885.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] All three of these engines used surface carburetors, which operated by moving air across the top of a vessel containing the fuel.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The first float-fed carburetor design, which used an atomizer nozzle, was introduced by German engineers Wilhelm Maybach and Gottlieb Daimler in their 1885 *Grandfather Clock engine*.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The Butler Petrol Cycle car—built in England in 1888—also used a float-fed carburetor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In 1892 Maybach produced an important carburetor with a jet spraying into a venturi, as would become the norm; this was patented in 1893.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The first carburetor for a stationary engine was patented in 1893 by Hungarian engineers János Csonka and Donát Bánki.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The first four-barrel carburetors were the Carter Carburetor WCFB and the identical Rochester 4GC, introduced in various General Motors models for 1952.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Oldsmobile referred the new carburetor as the "Quadri-Jet" (original spelling) while Buick called it the "Airpower".
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In the United States, carburetors were the common method of fuel delivery for most US-made gasoline (petrol) engines until the late 1980s, when fuel injection became the preferred method.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] One of the last motorsport users of carburetors was NASCAR, which switched to electronic fuel injection after the 2011 Sprint Cup series.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] NASCAR still uses the four-barrel carburetor in the NASCAR Xfinity Series.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] In Europe, carburetors were largely replaced by fuel injection in the late 1980s, although fuel injection had been increasingly used in luxury cars and sports cars since the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] EEC legislation required all vehicles sold and produced in member countries to have a catalytic converter after December 1992.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This legislation had been in the pipeline for some time, with many cars becoming available with catalytic converters or fuel injection from around 1990.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A significant concern for aircraft engines is the formation of ice inside the carburetor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The temperature of air within the carburetor can be reduced by up to 40 °C (72 °F), due to a combination of the reduced air pressure in the venturi and the latent heat of the evaporating fuel.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The conditions during the descent to landing are particularly conducive to icing, since the engine is run at idle for a prolonged period with the throttle closed.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Icing can also occur in cruise conditions at altitude.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A carburetor heat system is often used to prevent icing.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] This system consists of a secondary air intake which passes around the exhaust, in order to heat the air before it enters the carburetor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Typically, the system is operated by the pilot manually switching the intake air to travel via the heated intake path as required.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] The carburetor heat system reduces the power output (due to the lower density of heated air) and causes the intake air filter to be bypassed, therefore the system is only used when there is a risk of icing.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] If the engine is operating at idle RPM, another method to prevent icing is to periodically open the throttle, which increases the air temperature within the carburetor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Carburetor icing also occurs on other applications and various methods have been employed to solve this problem.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] On inline engines the intake and exhaust manifolds are on the same side of the head.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Heat from the exhaust is used to warm the intake manifold and in turn the carburetor.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] On V configurations, exhaust gases were directed from one head through the intake cross over to the other head.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] One method for regulating the exhaust flow on the cross over for intake warming was a weighted eccentric butterfly valve called a heat riser that remained closed at idle and opened at higher exhaust flow.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] Some vehicles used a heat stove around the exhaust manifold.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] It was connected to the air filter intake via tubing and supplied warmed air to the air filter.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carburetor] A vacuum controlled butterfly valve pre heat tube on the intake horn of the air cleaner would open allowing cooler air when engine load increased.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] The **Carter Carburetor Company** was an American manufacturer of carburetors, primarily for the automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] Louis, Missouri, in 1909 and ceased operation in 1985.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] Founder William Carter started experimenting with automotive carburetors while running a successful bicycle shop.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] His first, a cast brass model, could meter and deliver fuel more accurately than many competing units.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] He sold Carter Carburetor Company 13 years after founding it to American Car and Foundry Company.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] Carl Breer wrote that, upon learning that the Ball family (owners of Ball & Ball) was planning to leave the carburetor business, he set them up with Carter, which continued to produce the Ball & Ball basic designs used by Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] Carter adapted carburetors for Willys Jeep four-cylinder engines, waterproofing them for water crossings and making it possible to keep the engine going even on a steep incline (the YS carburetor).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] Carter also produced the first American four-barrel carburetor, used for Buick’s 1952 straight-eight, and followed by the William Carter Four-Barrel (WCFB) on the 1955 Chrysler C300.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] This was eventually superseded by the Aluminum Four-Barrel (AFB) and Air Valve Secondaries (AVS) models.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] The final Chrysler use of four-barrel Carter carburetors was the Thermo-Quad, which used a lightweight thermoplastic float bowl, on the most powerful Chrysler engines.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] Carter produced Rochester Quadrajet carburetors for their rival maker whenever demand outpaced Rochester's ability to make them.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] They were identical to Rochester's units, except the Carter name was stamped into the body.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] In Carter's final years in the early 1980s, they also produced Weber carburetors under license, such as the three-barrel Type 40IDA sold as replacements (or fuel injection retrofits) for 1960s and 1970s Porsche 911 S.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] In 1984, with fuel injection having replaced carburetors on most cars, the plant closed.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] In 1985, American Car and Foundry shut down the entire Carter Carburetor foundry, a year later ceding the PCB-contaminated property to the City of St.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] The site contains contaminants including TCE and PCBs that penetrate the topsoil to bedrock.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/carter-carburetor] In 2013, cleanup was estimated to cost US$30 million.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The **Chrysler B and RB engines** are a series of big-block V8 gasoline engines introduced in 1958 to replace the Chrysler FirePower (first generation Hemi) engines.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The B and RB engines are often referred to as "wedge" engines because they use wedge-shaped combustion chambers; this differentiates them from Chrysler's 426 Hemi big block engines that are typically referred to as "Hemi" or "426 Hemi" due to their hemispherical shaped combustion chambers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The corporation had been seeking a smaller and lighter replacement for its FirePower engines, in part because new styling dictates meant moving the engine forward in the chassis which negatively affected weight distribution.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] In order to provide a lower hood and center of gravity, the engine to be mounted lower than before.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Apart from changing the engine dimensions and engine mount position, this also entailed reconsidering the distributor drive and oil pump locations.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The oil pump could not be allowed to extend below the crank throw to avoid interfering with the steering linkage.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The engineers moved the distributor to the front of the engine, at a 45-degree angle, which cleared the heater while allowing the oil pump to be located in front of the block - above the bottom of the crank's throw, clearing the steering linkage.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 'B' series wedge engine was introduced in 1958 with 350 cu in (5.7 L) and 361 cu in (5.9 L) versions.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 361 would continue in production until the end of the series, albeit only for truck installation.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The RB ("raised B") arrived one year after the launch of the B series engines, in 383 cu in (6.3 L) and 413 cu in (6.8 L) displacements.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Unlike the previous B-engines, which had a 3+3⁄8-inch (85.7 mm) stroke, the RB engines had a 3+3⁄4-inch (95.3 mm) stroke.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] For 1960, a "ram induction" system increased the 413's torque up to 495 lb⋅ft (671 N⋅m) on the Chrysler 300F versions.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The last 'B-RB' wedge-headed engine was produced in August 1978, ending the era of Chrysler "big-block" engines.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] All Low Block B-series engines have a 3+3⁄8 in (85.7 mm) stroke, a 9.98 in (253 mm) deck height and 6.358 in (161.5 mm) connecting rods, resulting in a 1.88:1 rod ratio.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 350 cu in (5,735 cc) B engine was, along with the 361, the first production B engine, first available in 1958.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 350 is classified as a big-block engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] All parts except for the pistons are fully compatible with the 361.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 361 cu in B engine also introduced in 1958 was essentially the same as the 350 except with a larger 4+1⁄8 in (105 mm; 4.12 in) bore, for an actual displacement of 360.83 cu in (5,913 cc).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] In 1962, the Dodge Polara 500 came standard with a 305 bhp (227 kW) version of the 361 that had a four-barrel carburetor, dual-point distributor, and dual exhausts.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Plymouth called their versions of the early B engine the *Commando*, variants of which included the *Golden Commando* and *Sonoramic Commando*.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] DeSoto's B engine was named *Turboflash* and produced 295 bhp (220 kW).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The Dodge standard version was a 2-barrel with 295 bhp (220 kW) called the *Super Red Ram* with an optional variant that was called the *D500* and produced 320 bhp (239 kW).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 361 would last until the end of the series, albeit for trucks only.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] In its early years, the 305-horsepower 361 was optional on many vehicles, and standard on, among others, the Dodge 880.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 361 had a fuel-injected version in 1958 only.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Very few of the fuel-injected B engines were made and only a handful remain, since most were brought back to the dealer to be fitted with carburetors.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 383 cu in B engine—not to be confused with the RB version—was essentially a larger bore version of the 350 and 361, using a 4.25 in (108.0 mm) bore for a 383.03 cu in (6,277 cc) displacement.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] This venerable engine was introduced in 1959.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Dodge's version, the *D500*, had a cross-ram induction manifold and dual four-barrel carburetors as options.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] In some Dodge applications, this engine was labeled as the *Magnum*, while the Plymouth version was called the *Golden Commando*.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Both came with a dual point distributor in high-performance versions.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 383 became the standard model Mopar performance engine for the next decade.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The big bore allowed for larger, 2.08 in (53 mm), intake valves, and the relatively short stroke helped it to be a free-revving and free-breathing engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Producing a maximum of 330 hp (246 kW; 335 PS) (gross) and 460 lb⋅ft (624 N⋅m) of torque for the 1960 model year, the 383 beat the 392 Hemi that had reached 435 lb⋅ft (590 N⋅m).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 1960 383 engines featured the same basic ram induction system as the Chrysler 300F's 413 RB engines (named *Sonoramic Commando* when sold in Plymouth form).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The later 383 Magnum (starting in 1968) used the 440 Magnum heads, camshaft, and exhaust manifolds.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] This engine was advertised at 335 hp (250 kW; 340 PS).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 400 cu in (6.6 L) B engine was introduced in 1972 to replace the venerable 383, and were power-rated via the net (installed) method.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Chrysler increased the bore size of the 383 to create the 400.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Its bore of 4.342-inch (110.3 mm) was the largest used in any production Chrysler V8 at the date of its introduction.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] All parts except for the pistons were interchangeable between the 383 and 400.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] All three versions used the same 8.2:1 compression ratio.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 400 was used in car, truck, and motorhome chassis.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Horsepower and torque ratings gradually declined through the years because of the addition of more federally mandated emissions controls, until all Chrysler passenger vehicle big-block production ceased in 1978.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] For its last year of production, it only produced 190 hp (142 kW) (although a heavy-duty version was also available).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The *RB* engines, produced from 1959 to 1979, are raised-block (taller) versions of the B engines.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] All RB engines have a 3+3⁄4 in (95.3 mm) stroke, with the bore being the defining factor in engine size.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] All RB wedge engines share a deck height of 10.725 in (272.4 mm), and were fitted with 6.768 in (171.9 mm) long connecting rods, resulting in a 1.80:1 rod ratio.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Bore center distance is 4.8 in (120 mm).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] It was only available in 1959 and 1960 on the U.S.-built Chrysler Windsors and Saratogas; one of Trenton Engine's lines had been converted to the new RB engine (to make the 413), and demand for the 383 B engine was too high for the remaining line.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The solution was to create a 383 RB to fill the gap until the plant figured out how to quickly switch from one block to the other.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] It was also used in medium and heavy trucks including truck-tractors such as the C-1000, up until 1979.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] During that period, it powered almost all Chrysler New Yorker and all Imperial models, and was also available on the lesser Chryslers, Dodge Polara, Dodge Monaco, and Plymouth Fury as an alternative to the B-block 383 and the A-block 318.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] It was also fitted to some European cars such as the later Facel Vega Facel II.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] In the 1959 Chrysler 300E, the 413 wedge was fitted with inline dual four-barrel carburetors; it was factory-rated at 380 bhp (283 kW) at 5,000 rpm and 525 lb⋅ft (712 N⋅m) at 3,600 rpm.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] In 1960, a long-tube ram induction system was made standard on the Chrysler 300.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] It continued as standard on the 1961 300-G, and remained on the option sheets for Chrysler 300s through 1964.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] In 1962, a special version known as the "Max Wedge" was made available for drag racing and street use; this version produced 420 bhp (313 kW) at 5,000 rpm.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Not to be confused with the 426 Hemi, the 426 cu in (7.0 L) RB was a wedge-head RB block with a 4.25 in (108 mm) bore.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 426 Wedge served as Chrysler's main performance engine until the introduction of the 426 Hemi.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] For 1963, horsepower ratings would slightly increase (see below), and it became optional in B-bodied Dodges and Plymouths.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] After 1963, it would be used only in Dodges and Plymouths.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The Max Wedge was a race-only version of the 426 Wedge engine offered from the factory.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Known as the Super Stock Plymouth and Ramcharger Dodge, the Max Wedge featured high-flow cylinder heads developed through then state-of-the-art airflow testing.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] It had 1+7⁄8 in (48 mm) exhaust valves, which required the cylinder bores to be notched for clearance.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The blocks were a special severe-duty casting with larger oil-feed passages than other RB engines, and were stress-relieved by the factory.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Induction came by means of a cross-ram intake manifold tuned for peak power above 4000 rpm and two Carter AFB-3447SA 4-barrel carburetors.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The Max Wedge also included high-flow cast-iron exhaust manifolds that, on the later versions, resembled steel tube headers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The Max Wedge was factory rated at 415 or 425 bhp (309 or 317 kW) (depending on compression), and 480 lb⋅ft (651 N⋅m) at 4400 rpm.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Before the end of the 1963 model year, Chrysler introduced the Stage II Max Wedge with improved combustion chamber design and an improved camshaft.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The last performance year for the Max Wedge was the 1964 Stage III.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The factory-advertised power rating never changed despite the Stage II and III improvements.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] A *426 Street Wedge* engine was also available in 1964 and 1965.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] An increased-bore version of the standard New Yorker 413 single 4-barrel engine, it bears little relation to the Max Wedge except for basic architecture and dimensions.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] It was available only in B-body cars (Plymouth and Dodge) and light-duty Dodge D Series trucks.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 440 cu in (7.2 L) RB was produced from 1965 until 1978, making it the last version of the Chrysler RB block.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] It had a light wall construction, precision cast-iron block, with iron heads and a bore of 4.32 in (109.7 mm), for an overall displacement of 440 cu in (7.2 L).
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The new rating system produced lower, more realistic numbers for any given engine.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] At the same time, emissions regulations were requiring cleaner exhaust.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Engines including the 440 were made with reduced compression, modified cam timing, and other tuning measures to comply with the newly tightened emissions regulations.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The 1972 440 produced 335 bhp (250 kW) (gross) at 4400 rpm; the new net rating was 225 hp (168 kW)—which very closely coincided with period German DIN ratings and TÜV measurements.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] The high-output 440 (4-barrel/mild cam/dual exhausts) was marketed as the *Magnum* in Dodges, the *Super Commando* in Plymouths, and the *TNT* in Chryslers.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] It was also available in marine and heavy-duty commercial applications until that year.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] Chrysler also offers complete new 'crate' engines through its Mopar parts division in various displacements.
[src:chrysler-b-engine/chrysler-b-engine] These engines are built from entirely new parts.
